WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.920
Hi, my name's Charlotte Wickham and I'm a Developer Educator at Posit.

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:17.400
In this video, I'll show you how to create a Quarto Document in Positron.

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:22.280
Here I am in Positron, and you can see from the File Explorer I've got a folder open

00:00:22.280 --> 00:00:27.840
called Penguins, but there's nothing in it, except I have set up a virtual environment

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:33.599
with uv, you could use pip or conda, or perhaps you're using R. You can see that the Python

00:00:33.599 --> 00:00:39.000
from that environment is active up in the Session Picker, and that it is running down

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:40.000
in my console.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.040
The first thing I'm going to do is open up a new Quarto Document, and there's lots of

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:49.880
ways to do that, one of which is to use this New button, say I want a new file, and then

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:52.880
pick Quarto Document from the dropdown.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:56.759
I like to use the Command Palette, so I'm going to open up the Command Palette with

00:00:56.759 --> 00:01:03.000
Command Shift P, or Control Shift P, start typing Quarto to see the Quarto commands,

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:05.839
and select Quarto New Document.

00:01:05.839 --> 00:01:09.839
Either way, you're going to end up with a new Quarto Document, it's going to have some

00:01:09.839 --> 00:01:13.760
boilerplate in the YAML header, but otherwise no other content.

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:19.040
So I'm going to go ahead and change that title to Penguins, and I'm going to save that file,

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:22.959
I'm going to call it penguins.qmd.

00:01:22.959 --> 00:01:27.879
The content in a Quarto file is Markdown, so I can just start typing Markdown, hash

00:01:27.879 --> 00:01:32.879
hash is Markdown for a header, so I might have an introduction, and I might just say

00:01:32.879 --> 00:01:43.680
this is an exploration of the penguins data.

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:49.360
So you can write Markdown here in the Source Editor, Positron comes with a Visual Editor

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:55.400
too, you can use this toggle up here to switch to it, and in that Visual Editor it appears

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:59.639
a little bit more like how it's going to render, and there's some tools in there to help you

00:01:59.639 --> 00:02:02.480
write that Markdown syntax if it's a little unfamiliar.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:06.120
Let me jump back to the Source Editor.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:07.839
So a couple of things to note.

00:02:07.839 --> 00:02:13.240
The command I used to create that document, Quarto Create New Document, is being provided

00:02:13.279 --> 00:02:15.559
by the Quarto extension.

00:02:15.559 --> 00:02:21.000
But because the Quarto extension comes pre-installed with Positron, you have all those commands

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:22.600
from the start.

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:28.320
The other thing to notice is down in the status bar, you'll see what version of Quarto Positron's

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:29.320
picked up.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:34.759
If you've never installed Quarto before, you'll just get the Quarto that's bundled with Positron.

00:02:34.759 --> 00:02:38.440
If you have installed it before, you'll see the version of Quarto that you might have

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:43.000
installed before, and if you need to update it, you can just head to quarto.org, grab

00:02:43.759 --> 00:02:46.039
the new version, and Positron will pick it up.

00:02:46.039 --> 00:02:48.399
Now we have this very minimal Quarto document.

00:02:48.399 --> 00:02:51.800
I'm going to get Quarto to render it so we can see what it looks like.

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:53.039
There's a couple of ways to do that.

00:02:53.039 --> 00:02:57.039
Again, there's this button, Preview, up in the Editor toolbar.

00:02:57.039 --> 00:02:59.559
There's a command, Quarto Preview.

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:00.639
There's also a shortcut.

00:03:00.639 --> 00:03:05.240
I'm going to use the shortcut Command Shift K or Control Shift K.

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:09.559
And when I hit that shortcut, you'll notice what happens is down in the terminal, Quarto

00:03:09.559 --> 00:03:10.559
is running.

00:03:10.600 --> 00:03:15.240
The command it's running is Quarto Preview on this document I have open in the Editor.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:19.360
And once it's finished rendering, it's going to pop up that preview in the Viewer pane

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:20.600
in Positron.

00:03:20.600 --> 00:03:25.800
So now we've got the side-by-side view of our source in the Editor and our rendered

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:28.080
document previewing in the Viewer.

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:32.000
The other thing to note is that when that document got previewed, it got fully rendered

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.559
and out came the file penguins.html, and you can see that that is in our folder over here

00:03:38.559 --> 00:03:40.559
in the File Explorer.

00:03:40.559 --> 00:03:46.080
Of course, the power of Quarto isn't in turning Markdown into HTML documents.

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.860
It's being able to incorporate code and its output into those documents.

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:53.559
So let's go ahead and add some code to this document.

00:03:53.559 --> 00:03:56.800
Before I go ahead and add a code cell, I'm just going to add a few requirements to my

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:57.800
virtual environment.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:01.600
So down in the terminal, not in the Quarto Preview terminal, I'm going to leave that

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:02.600
preview running.

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:07.800
But in another terminal, I'm going to add some requirements.

00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:13.399
The first one I'm going to add is Jupyter, so uv pip install Jupyter.

00:04:13.399 --> 00:04:18.320
And Jupyter is required by Quarto to be able to execute Python code cells.

00:04:18.320 --> 00:04:23.000
So if you've got Python code cells, you're going to need the Jupyter package.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.519
And then the other thing I'm going to install is Plot9.

00:04:25.519 --> 00:04:28.480
This is now my analysis-specific.

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:34.920
I'm going to make some plots with Plot9, so I'm going to install that package as well.

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:37.000
Now we can go ahead and add a code cell.

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:39.079
And again, there's lots of ways to do this.

00:04:39.079 --> 00:04:42.239
There's an Insert Code Cell button up in the toolbar.

00:04:42.239 --> 00:04:44.320
There's a shortcut for that.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:48.640
There's also a command for that called Quarto Insert Code Cell.

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:54.079
I'm going to click that button, and then a dropdown comes up for which language this

00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:56.880
code cell will be in, and I want a Python code cell.

00:04:56.880 --> 00:04:59.000
So I just hit Enter for that.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:00.559
So now I can write my Python code.

00:05:00.559 --> 00:05:04.079
The first thing I want to do is import some packages.

00:05:04.079 --> 00:05:14.079
So from Plot9, I'm going to import all the functions, and from Plot9 Data, I'm going

00:05:14.079 --> 00:05:17.079
to import penguins.

00:05:17.079 --> 00:05:18.679
Now I'm just writing this code in a code cell.

00:05:18.679 --> 00:05:21.059
I haven't done anything to execute it.

00:05:21.059 --> 00:05:25.519
But the nice thing here is it's really easy to take this code and send it down to my console.

00:05:25.519 --> 00:05:28.119
Again, lots of ways to do it.

00:05:28.119 --> 00:05:31.839
There's this Run Cell button that'll appear above any code cell.

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:35.880
If I click that, it sends it off to my console.

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:38.440
You can also do this with keyboard shortcuts.

00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:44.959
So Command or Control Enter will send one line, your current line, to the console.

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:50.679
Or if you do Command or Control Shift Enter, you'll get all the lines in that code cell

00:05:50.679 --> 00:05:52.839
sent down to the console.

00:05:52.839 --> 00:05:56.880
That makes it really easy to write your code here in the Quarto document and just send

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:59.320
it down to the console when you're ready.

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:00.519
Let me add another code cell.

00:06:00.519 --> 00:06:06.920
This time I'm going to use the keyboard shortcut, and I'm actually going to try and make a plot

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:08.320
using Plot9.

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:10.640
So there's the ggplot function.

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:15.720
And you'll notice that in this code cell in a Quarto document, you get all the help you

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:21.200
would expect from code in a script document in Positron.

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:27.200
So I'm getting completions, I'm getting this pop-up help for functions, that kind of thing.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:31.279
I am going to make a plot of this penguin's data.

00:06:31.279 --> 00:06:37.399
And on the x-axis, I'm going to have FlipperLength in millimeters.

00:06:37.399 --> 00:06:39.399
It's a very long variable name.

00:06:39.399 --> 00:06:45.760
And on the y-axis, I'm going to have BillLength in millimeters.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:49.519
And I need to add a geom to make sure there's something in my plot.

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:54.480
So again, I can use my keyboard shortcut to send that to the console.

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:59.000
You'll notice that a code gets run down in the console, and the plot pops up in this

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:00.959
Plots pane.

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:04.899
And we were looking at the viewer, we were looking at our preview of the Quarto document.

00:07:04.899 --> 00:07:08.440
When that plot popped up, Positron switched back to the Session pane.

00:07:08.440 --> 00:07:13.720
You can see this is where all the information is about what's in my Python session, and

00:07:13.720 --> 00:07:16.959
also the current plot from Python.

00:07:16.959 --> 00:07:19.519
I'm going to add a little bit extra here.

00:07:19.519 --> 00:07:26.040
I'm just going to set the color of these points to be the species variable.

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:29.279
And I can rerun that, and there's my new plot.

00:07:29.279 --> 00:07:33.000
There are other ways to run cells in Quarto documents.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.119
So you can see now I've got two code cells.

00:07:36.119 --> 00:07:38.160
There's a little bit of an extra command up here.

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:41.839
I can run all the cells above this one.

00:07:41.839 --> 00:07:45.600
So that's really useful if you've restarted your session, just want to run everything

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:47.359
up to this point.

00:07:47.359 --> 00:07:51.000
You can see in the previous, there was a Run Next Cell button.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And if you bring up the command palette, you'll see if you look for Quarto Run, there's a

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:01.119
ton of different commands you can use to run cells and do various things, and they've all

00:08:01.119 --> 00:08:02.760
got shortcuts there.

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:05.079
Okay, so I'm pretty happy with that plot.

00:08:05.079 --> 00:08:06.760
We've had a look in the Plots pane.

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:10.040
This has all been running in my interactive console.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:13.119
But let's take a look at how my Quarto document is looking now.

00:08:13.119 --> 00:08:15.200
So I'm going to rerun that preview command.

00:08:15.519 --> 00:08:18.320
Let me do it by clicking the button this time.

00:08:18.320 --> 00:08:19.679
So in the background, Quarto is running.

00:08:19.679 --> 00:08:25.279
You can see down in the status bar for a moment, it said rendering this document.

00:08:25.279 --> 00:08:28.399
Once it's done, up pops that new preview.

00:08:28.399 --> 00:08:34.640
And there is our document now with our code cells and that plot.

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:37.880
Now there's a few things that are bothering me about this document at the moment.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:40.799
One of them, you'll notice there was a warning about some missing values.

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:43.679
So I should certainly investigate what that was about.

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:47.000
But if I just want to get rid of it in my output, that's something I can do with the

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:48.799
code cell option in Quarto.

00:08:48.799 --> 00:08:52.960
So code cell options start with a comment character followed by a pipe, and then you

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:55.200
write the code cell option.

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:59.119
And in Positron, you can get help on what possible options you might have by hitting

00:08:59.119 --> 00:09:01.599
Command Space.

00:09:01.599 --> 00:09:03.440
And these are the completions on offer.

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:08.880
I'm looking for the one that is warning, and I'm going to set it to false.

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:14.080
So this is part of the sort of YAML intelligence you get through the Quarto extension in

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:15.760
Positron.

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:21.520
Now if I repreview that document, you'll notice that that warning is omitted from the output.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:23.359
So I'm going to go back up to the header.

00:09:23.359 --> 00:09:27.280
This is also using YAML syntax.

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:29.359
And I'm going to change one thing about my document.

00:09:29.359 --> 00:09:31.520
I don't actually want any of the code to show up.

00:09:31.520 --> 00:09:36.960
So there's an option called echo, and it takes a few values, one of which is false, which

00:09:37.039 --> 00:09:39.599
just says do not echo the code in my document.

00:09:39.599 --> 00:09:43.840
If I repreview, you'll see that that code is no longer in the document.

00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:48.719
So another great thing about Quarto is that you're not limited to sending things to HTML.

00:09:48.719 --> 00:09:52.159
So right now, I've got format HTML up in the header here.

00:09:52.159 --> 00:09:55.679
If you want to just take a look at what it might look like in a different format, there's

00:09:55.679 --> 00:10:01.760
another Quarto command called preview, just like we've been running, but it's called preview

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:02.400
format.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:05.520
So if you hit that command, it's going to give you some options.

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:10.080
It's going to start with any formats that are actually defined in the YAML header, and

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:11.119
then give some other options.

00:10:11.119 --> 00:10:14.559
So let me have a look at this PDF via Typed.

00:10:14.559 --> 00:10:15.840
So this is format Typed.

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:19.679
Typed is an alternative to LaTeX.

00:10:19.679 --> 00:10:21.359
It creates PDFs.

00:10:21.359 --> 00:10:24.080
One of the great things about it is it's bundled in Quarto.

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:28.479
So you can create PDFs with Quarto without any other installations.

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:33.919
And up pops a preview of it that's now a PDF document.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.080
And I'm viewing that in the viewer pane.

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:41.039
If I run preview again, so now I'm just using the shortcut, it's going to stick with that

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:43.359
format that I selected from preview format.

00:10:43.359 --> 00:10:48.559
If I want to go back to HTML, I'm going to need to rerun that preview format command

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:51.039
and get back to HTML.

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:56.479
So if I'm happy with this document, the last thing I want to do is put it somewhere where

00:10:56.479 --> 00:10:58.080
I can share it with other people.

00:10:58.799 --> 00:11:03.119
So one of the ways to do that with Quarto is through its Quarto publish command.

00:11:03.119 --> 00:11:06.400
So down in the terminal, I'm going to kill that Quarto preview process.

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:07.679
I just hit control C.

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:11.520
And I'm going to run the command Quarto publish.

00:11:12.159 --> 00:11:16.239
And I'm going to tell it I want to publish this document, the standalone document.

00:11:16.239 --> 00:11:17.599
So penguins.qmd.

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:22.000
And Quarto publish will pop up a list of places you can publish.

00:11:22.799 --> 00:11:26.640
I'm going to choose Quarto pub because that's just a really easy, quick way to get started.

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:32.159
I already have an account on Quarto pub with my email address.

00:11:33.599 --> 00:11:36.559
And it's going to ask me what I want to call this document.

00:11:36.559 --> 00:11:37.760
I'll just call it penguins.

00:11:38.479 --> 00:11:39.840
And Quarto will handle the rest.

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:42.880
It's going to rerender that document, make sure it's up to date.

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:45.200
It's going to send all those files up to Quarto pub.

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:51.679
And then once it's done, it's actually going to open up a browser and send us to view that

00:11:51.679 --> 00:11:52.400
document.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:55.679
And you can see that that document now lives on Quarto.pub.

00:11:55.679 --> 00:11:57.119
And this is a public URL.

00:11:57.119 --> 00:12:00.080
Anyone else can visit this and see my document.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:03.039
That's it for our walkthrough of Quarto and Positron.

00:12:03.039 --> 00:12:06.960
If you head to the Positron docs, you can learn a bit more about the relationship between

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:08.080
Quarto and Positron.

00:12:08.080 --> 00:12:13.119
But if you want more detail, the best place to go is the Quarto documentation site.

00:12:13.119 --> 00:12:17.200
There we have a tutorial for learning about Quarto in Positron.

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:21.200
And you can work through the examples there, either using Python or using R.

00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:26.640
There's also a whole section in our tools section of our guide all about using Positron

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:27.440
with Quarto.

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:30.479
I hope you enjoy making Quarto documents in Positron.

